# Intuition
Opening parenthesis decreases the counter and closing parenthesis increases the counter
```
   (  (  )  (  ) )  (  (  ) )
0 -1 -2 -1 -2 -1 0 -1 -2 -1 0
```

There is always a primitive string after a zero till next zero.
We just need to remove first and last character of primitive string.

So the intution is...
If you get c=0 do not take that character and the character next to it.

# Approach
If you encounter c=0, it means previous substring was primitive. So the position at which you are currently, must be opening parenthesis. Make c= -1 and continue.
```
 if (c == 0) {
        c--;
        continue;
      }
```

If you got Opening parenthesis decreases the counter else for closing parenthesis increases the counter.
```
      if (s[i] == '(') c--;
      else c++;
```

If you got c=0, this is last character of primitive parenthesis. Therefore do not push it into ans str.
```
      if (c == 0) continue;
```

Else push it into ans string.
```
      str.push_back(s[i]);
```

# Code
```
class Solution {
  public: string removeOuterParentheses(string s) {
    string str;
    int c = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
      if (c == 0) {
        c--;
        continue;
      }
      if (s[i] == '(') c--;
      else c++;
      if (c == 0) continue;
      str.push_back(s[i]);
    }
    return str;
  }
};
```

# Complexity
```
- Time complexity: O(n)
```

```
- Space complexity: O(1)
