solutions.content:
I took this as a drill in different coding styles:

1. Destructive | Functional Style - Using `scan()` to have an accumulator state, and the idiom `for_each(drop)` to consume the iterator without using it ([https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/48945](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/48945)).

```
impl Solution {
    pub fn running_sum(mut nums: Vec<i32>) -> Vec<i32> {
        nums.iter_mut()
            .scan(0, |prev, curr| {
                *curr += *prev;
                *prev = *curr;
                Some(())
            })
            .for_each(drop);
        nums
    }
}
```

2. Non-destructive | Functional - OK, `nums` is owned by `running_sum()`, so it's destroyed anyway when it goes out of scope, but say you wanted to continue using `nums` later on, this is the way to do it.

```
impl Solution {
    pub fn running_sum(nums: Vec<i32>) -> Vec<i32> {
        nums.into_iter()
            .scan(0, |prev, curr| {
                *prev += curr;
                Some(*prev)
            })
            .collect()
    }
}
```

3. Destructive | Imperative - We are a person who likes manual indexing. We think we know better than the compiler how things should be done efficiently. :) Since we own `nums`, why not use it for the return value to avoid allocating another vector?

```
impl Solution {
    pub fn running_sum(mut nums: Vec<i32>) -> Vec<i32> {
        for i in 1..nums.len() {
            nums[i] += nums[i-1];
        }
        nums
    }
}
```

4. Non-destructive | Imperative - We want to contine using `nums` and we like loops. We preallocate `rez` to avoid reallocations, and we use iterators to avoid manual indexing.

```
impl Solution {
    pub fn running_sum(nums: Vec<i32>) -> Vec<i32> {
        let mut rez = vec![0; nums.len()];
        let mut acc = 0;
        for (src, dst) in nums.iter().zip(rez.iter_mut()) {
            acc += *src;
            *dst = acc;
        }
        rez
    }
}
```

