solutions.content:
I notice most people did this iteratively, but you could also use recursion:

Another note, I'm seeing people use an accumulator outside their loops to track the sum. You don't need that, just start on the second element, index 1, and sum the current element with the previous one. There's never a need to iterate over the first element, because the running sum at that element is already equal to the element itself. For that reason we can simply check for inputs of size 1 (or 0) and return them as is.

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> runningSum(vector<int>& nums) {
        if(nums.size() <= 1) {
            return nums;
        }
        recur(nums, 1);
        return nums;
    }

    void recur(vector<int>& nums, int count) {
        if(count == nums.size()) {
            return;
        }
        nums.at(count) = nums.at(count) + nums.at(count - 1);
        recur(nums, count+1);
    }
};
```

